{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"90850088-256d-4412-b60a-e5bf25b2d70c","content":"These are two separate breaking changes in C# 15:\n\n---\n\n**1. `&&` with `dynamic` and user-defined operators**\n\nThe `&&` operator is compound — it desugars into `operator false(x) ? x : operator &(x, y)`. When one operand is `dynamic`, the dynamic binder cannot properly implement this short-circuit pattern (it doesn't know to call `operator false` then `operator &` in sequence). Earlier compilers silently deferred this to runtime where it could fail unpredictably. C# 15 now rejects it at compile time.\n\n**Fix:** Avoid combining `&&` with `dynamic`. Either cast or split the logic:\n\n```csharp\n// Option A: cast away dynamic\nvar combined = left && (IFilter)right;\n\n// Option B: desugar manually\nIFilter combined = IFilter.false(left) ? left : (IFilter)(left & right);\n```\n\n---\n\n**2. `ref readonly` lambda — CS0518**\n\nCS0518 means a predefined BCL type required by the compiler is missing. For `ref readonly`-returning lambdas, the compiler must synthesize a delegate type annotated with a new attribute (likely in `System.Runtime.CompilerServices`). If your project isn't actually targeting `net11.0` — or you're on a preview SDK that hasn't shipped the updated BCL types — the compiler recognizes the syntax but can't find the supporting type.\n\n**Fix options:**\n\n```csharp\n// Option A: ensure your project targets net11.0\n<TargetFramework>net11.0</TargetFramework>\n\n// Option B: declare an explicit delegate type instead of relying\n// on synthesized delegates with `var`\ndelegate ref readonly int RefReadOnlyFunc();\nRefReadOnlyFunc fn = () => ref value;\n```\n\nCheck your `.csproj` — a common cause is upgrading the SDK (getting C# 15 syntax) without updating `TargetFramework` from `net10.0`/`net9.0` to `net11.0`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"53091af1-0aa0-4094-9655-ff47ceb3f141","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about two compiler errors they're encountering after upgrading to .NET 11 / C# 15. Let me analyze each one.\n\n**Error 1: `left && right` where `left` is `IFilter` and `right` is `dynamic`**\n\nIn C# 15 / .NET 11, there's a known breaking change related to how the compiler handles short-circuit operators (`&&` / `||`) when one operand is `dynamic`. \n\nThe `&&` operator requires `operator &`, `operator true`, and `operator false`. When one operand is `dynamic`, the compiler needs to resolve these at compile time for the static type but defer some resolution to runtime.\n\n\nThe problem is that `IFilter` defines `operator true` and `operator false` as static members on the interface itself. In C# 15, the compiler has become stricter about how it handles user-defined short-circuiting operators on interfaces when mixed with `dynamic` operands, which is causing this compilation failure. the issue is that `IFilter` defines `operator true` and `operator false`, but `CompositeFilter` doesn't inherit them properly, or there's a mismatch in how the compiler resolves operators when dealing with interface types and `dynamic` operands in C# 15's stricter checking.\n\nActually, I think the real problem is that C# 14/.NET 10 introduced a breaking change where user-defined short-circuiting operators (`&&`/`||`) simply don't work with `dynamic` operands anymore—the dynamic binder can't properly handle the three-part pattern of `operator true`/`operator false` plus `operator &`/`operator |` at runtime. So I'd need to avoid using `&&` with dynamic values and instead use explicit type checks or casts.\n\nFor the `ref readonly` lambda issue, the CS0518 error suggests a missing BCL type. When you try to create a lambda with a `ref readonly` return type, the compiler needs to synthesize a delegate type to represent that, but the runtime doesn't have the necessary infrastructure to support `ref readonly` returns in delegate form, so it fails to find the required types. be available. In .NET 11 these should